# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-lakehouse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Iceberg was started at Netflix by Ryan Blue and Dan Weeks.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Apache Hive was used by many different services and engines in the Netflix infrastructure.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Hive was never able to guarantee correctness and did not provide stable atomic transactions.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Many at Netflix avoided using these services and making changes to the data to avert unintended consequences from the Hive format.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Improve performance by enabling finer-grained operations to be done at the file granularity for optimal writes.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Simplify and abstract general operation and maintenance of tables.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] The project was open-sourced and donated to the Apache Software Foundation in November 2018.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] In May 2020, the Iceberg project graduated to become a top-level Apache project.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Iceberg is used by multiple companies including Airbnb, Apple, Expedia, LinkedIn, Adobe, Lyft.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Apache Iceberg operates by abstracting table metadata from the underlying data storage.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] It maintains metadata files that track snapshots, schema information, partition layouts, and data file locations, enabling efficient and atomic table operations.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] At a high level, Iceberg organizes table data into snapshots.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Each snapshot represents the state of the table at a particular point in time, allowing Iceberg to provide ACID-compliant transactional capabilities, including snapshot isolation, concurrent writes, and rollback functionality.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] The snapshot metadata is managed as a tree structure of manifest files and metadata files stored within the file system.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Iceberg uses the Apache Parquet file format for storing actual data due to its efficient columnar storage structure, optimized for analytical queries.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Parquet files in Iceberg store table rows in a compressed, column-oriented format, significantly reducing storage costs and improving read performance through techniques such as predicate pushdown and column pruning.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Iceberg references Parquet files in manifest files, facilitating quick identification and access to relevant data during query execution.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Apache Iceberg employs a multi‐level metadata hierarchy for tracking table contents.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] At the top, a table metadata file (often metadata.json) stores table-level information—such as the schema, partition specifications, the list of snapshots, and pointers to the current "root" snapshot.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Each snapshot represents a consistent view of the table and is associated with a manifest list (an Avro file) that enumerates all manifest files for that snapshot.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] A manifest file is an index that lists a set of data files (e.g., Parquet files) along with metadata about each file – including row count, partition values, and column statistics such as minimum and maximum values.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] These manifests are small metadata files (often in Avro format) that segment the table’s metadata, enabling a distributed design whereby entire manifests can be pruned when querying by partition instead of requiring a single, giant file listing all data files.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] Moreover, Iceberg’s metadata tree provides an historic record of table changes—retaining old snapshots and manifests (thus enabling time travel) until they expire—and it can quickly plan queries by reading only the relevant manifest files rather than scanning all data files or directories.
[src:data-lakehouse/apache-iceberg] This approach avoids expensive operations such as directory listing and makes metadata access efficient even for huge tables.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:data-lakehouse/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:data-lakehouse/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
